Proposal for On-Premises Computational Chemistry Configuration 
 
1. The ask 
Four nodes were procured in the current infrastructure refresh: INSIIUKGPU01 and INSIIUKGPU02 (Heavy GPU compute, H200 NVL 141 GB HBM3e), INSIIUKCGPU01 (Lightweight GPU and inference, L4 24 GB GDDR6), and INSIIUKCPU01 (High-memory CPU, 128 vCPU / 512 GB RAM, no GPU). The procurement rationale, agreed during specification and purchase discussions, earmarked INSIIUKCGPU01 for Computational Chemistry services and one of the two H200 nodes for Computational Chemistry scientific workflows. The second H200 is available for broader use. 
This proposal formalises that allocation: INSIIUKCGPU01 as the Services node and INSIIUKGPU01 as the Development node for Computational Chemistry, allocated exclusively to the cheminformatics sub-account. INSIIUKGPU02 and INSIIUKCPU01 remain in the shared research pool for bioinformatics and statistical genetics. The two cheminformatics nodes are managed under a SLURM scheduler with partitions that guarantee quality of service for latency-sensitive inference while enabling fair share on long research runs (section 5). Computational Chemistry does not require the high-memory node, since the workload mix sits within the 256 GB host-RAM tier. 
The case for dedicated allocation rests on timing. Computational Chemistry is in an active build-out phase. The stack, workflows, and scientist-facing services are being established, validated, and handed to users. Operational stability during this period is essential, and ad-hoc reallocation or contention with unrelated workloads slows buildout significantly. This proposal requests a stable baseline, not an indefinite ring-fence. The allocation can be revisited through standard governance at any time should business priorities shift at iiuk or at Insmed. 
2. Rationale 
Four operational drivers reinforce the on-prem-with-scheduling approach. Interactive tooling (virtual screening UIs, model inference endpoints) suffers from cloud round-trip latency. Long-running jobs such as molecular dynamics, Boltz2 sampling, and Chemprop training are repeatedly disrupted by spot pre-emption, session time-outs, and scheduling contention on shared cloud pools. A proper scheduler on dedicated nodes protects user-facing services from being blocked behind multi-day research jobs, which is the failure mode that undifferentiated shared compute produces. The economics also favour on-prem: cloud compute and egress for our workload profile (sustained GPU utilisation, large local NVMe I/O, frequent result retrieval) are out of proportion to hardware and software already procured, with estimated cloud-equivalent spend of approximately £45 to 50k per year before storage and egress that this allocation avoids. 
Licensing reinforces the case. Schrödinger’s GPU-accelerated suite (Desmond, FEP+, WaterMap) uses hardware-bound licensing tied to the specific GPU device, and OpenEye (ROCS, OEDocking) uses node-locked licensing bound to MAC address. Cloud deployment of either creates recurrent licence invalidation at instance restart, requiring re-hosting requests with a 24 to 48 hour turnaround and risking mid-campaign outages on long-running FEP+ calculations. On-prem deployment provides stable, one-time licence binding. 
