Placement principle. Memory tier is the primary differentiator for job placement. Workloads requiring more than 256 GB host RAM must run on INSIIUKCPU01. GPU memory is the second axis: workloads exceeding the L4 24 GB ceiling must run on an H200 node (INSIIUKGPU01 or INSIIUKGPU02). The Computational Chemistry workload mix sits within the 256 GB host-RAM tier. Placement between INSIIUKCGPU01 and INSIIUKGPU01 is therefore driven by GPU memory and run length, not RAM. 
Hardware fit. The H200’s 141 GB HBM3e is essential for biophysics simulations (molecular dynamics and free-energy methods such as FEP+), co-folding (Boltz2), and model training. This capacity would be wasted on inference. The L4 is purpose-built for inference economics, handles CPU-bound workflows (ROCS, virtual screening, chemical, patent and reactions search) efficiently on the same box, and accommodates Glide docking, Maestro sessions, and small QSAR or ML inference within its 24 GB ceiling. 
Storage. Each node has approximately 7 TB of local NVMe RAID 0 scratch and access to NetApp NFS (INSUKNETAPP01, ONTAP 9.15.1P3, 2-node HA, NFSv4.1 with NFSv3 fallback, LACP-bonded) for persistent output. Local NVMe scratch drives per-node sizing. NetApp NFS persistent output drives long-term capacity planning. Local NVMe delivers sustained multi-GB/s throughput with microsecond latency, much faster than cloud persistent disk, and is required for multi-day FEP+ campaigns, MD trajectory I/O, and ML training-data access. Cloud ephemeral SSD matches throughput but is lost at instance stop, which is untenable for these workloads. Persistent storage uses the planned NetApp volume layout: reference data (compound libraries, prepared protein structures, ML training corpora) on vol_datasets; persistent outputs (cleaned trajectories, final models, MLflow artefacts) on vol_projects; software installs (Schrödinger, OpenEye, Spack tree) on vol_software; user homes on vol_home (snapshot-protected); retired campaigns on vol_archive. 20 to 30% of node scratch is reserved as headroom for OS, package cache, swap, and tool temporary files, per the sizing reference. The workload budgets in section 4 do not include this overhead. 
