Multifactor priority weights are configured to favour Fairshare within dev and QoS between partitions, with a moderate Age weight to prevent long-job starvation. Always-on services reserve a fixed share of INSIIUKCGPU01, sized during buildout (approximately 8 to 16 vCPU, 32 to 64 GB RAM, and a partial L4 share). Remaining capacity is available to services, batch, and interactive. Reservations are available on dev-gpu for multi-day FEP+ campaigns via a documented procedure. 
Access control 
Identity is provided by Active Directory via SSSD and Kerberos. A Unix-visible AD group for the Computational Chemistry team (provisionally compchem; final name to be confirmed by IT) maps to membership for access control. Access is enforced at three layers: 
1. SSH. AllowGroups compchem ops-admins on both nodes (the AD group exposed as a POSIX group through SSSD). Non-members are rejected at the SSH layer, with no shell and no SLURM submission. 
2. SLURM. All team members are associated with the cheminformatics sub-account under the research parent in slurmdbd (alongside bioinformatics and statistical_genetics under the same parent). All partitions on INSIIUKCGPU01 and INSIIUKGPU01 declare AllowAccounts=cheminformatics, which prevents jobs from other sub-accounts being scheduled on these nodes. 
3. Filesystem. Local /scratch is owned root:compchem mode 2770 (setgid); per-user subdirectories /scratch/$USER are mode 0750. NetApp paths mirror this configuration. 
Interactive use is gated through srun --pty or salloc into the interactive partition. The pam_slurm_adopt module binds SSH sessions to active allocations, which prevents users from running long-running sessions outside SLURM. Cross-team access is granted via a documented request that adds the user to compchem; there are no per-node exceptions and no shadow accounts. 
Inference API exposure and network access 
Always-on inference services are exposed as REST APIs over HTTPS, bound to specific ports on INSIIUKCGPU01 and routed through a single reverse proxy (nginx or traefik) running on the same node. The reverse proxy handles TLS termination, request routing to per-service ports, authentication enforcement, and rate limiting. 
1. Internal corporate network. API endpoints are reachable via internal DNS (for example compchem-api.iiuk.insmed.local resolving to INSIIUKCGPU01:443). No tunnel is required for users on the corporate LAN. 
2. Remote employees and external collaborators. Access is via IT-managed tunnel infrastructure (corporate VPN or equivalent), with an IP allowlist at the tunnel endpoint scoped to specific addresses agreed with IT (home offices, partner sites, other Insmed locations). The tunnel terminates inside the corporate network; from there the request reaches the same internal DNS endpoint. 
3. Service-to-service automation. KNIME workflows, scheduled jobs, and internal scripts call the same APIs over the internal network using service-account credentials. 
API authentication does not rely on network perimeter alone. Every endpoint enforces a token (API key, JWT, or mTLS depending on workload sensitivity) issued by the compchem service and tied to the requester’s Insmed identity. Audit logs of API calls are persisted on NetApp for compliance traceability. 
Accounting 
SLURM sacct and sreport provide per-user and per-project utilisation reporting. The Tier 2 and Tier 3 capacity-escalation triggers in section 6 are derived from this data over rolling 30-day windows. 
