Sizing implications. Approximately 7 TB scratch per node is sufficient for routine FEP+ medium campaigns, Chemprop and generative-model training, all services workloads, and reasonable concurrency on either node. Capacity becomes tight for very large FEP+ library screens running concurrently with other heavy GPU workloads on INSIIUKGPU01, which exceed comfortable scratch budget once the headroom reserve is applied and require campaign staging or scheduling separation. Scratch-pressure events will be flagged through SLURM accounting. 
Environment provisioning. Spack is used for system-level scientific software (GROMACS, OpenMM, AmberTools, MPI and BLAS variants, compiler toolchains, RDKit C++ extensions), exposed via Lmod-based module load. A spack.yaml environment file in version control pins versions for reproducibility. Singularity or Apptainer containers are used for user-defined workflow environments (Python ML stacks, inference REST services, custom toolchains), with baseline images maintained alongside Spack environments. Cluster configuration is codified as Ansible playbooks for reproducibility and recovery (in progress with Nick). Detailed configuration is being agreed with Nick. 
6. Risks and mitigations 
Single point of failure on Services node. Mitigated by fall-back of critical inference from INSIIUKCGPU01 to INSIIUKGPU01 via SLURM partition configuration, and short-term cloud burst capacity for sustained outages. 
SLURM configuration complexity. Mitigated by a deliberately simple partition design with QoS classes rather than a federated multi-cluster setup; supported by documented runbooks for common failure modes. 
Data durability on local NVMe scratch. Local NVMe is scratch, not primary storage. Persistent outputs are written to NetApp NFS at job completion. A nightly sync from scratch to NetApp covers anything left on-node overnight (target paths to be confirmed with IT). User guidance reinforces that scratch is ephemeral. 
Scratch pressure on Development node. Multi-TB FEP+ campaigns running concurrently with other heavy workloads can approach the 7 TB ceiling on INSIIUKGPU01 once headroom is reserved. Mitigated by SLURM scratch reservations on the dev-gpu partition for large campaigns, queue-time enforcement of campaign separation, and staging of intermediate trajectories to NetApp during long runs. 
External API access via IT tunnel. Exposing inference services beyond the corporate LAN expands attack surface. Mitigated by a tunnel-side IP allowlist scoped to specific addresses agreed with IT, per-API authentication independent of tunnel auth, TLS-only endpoints behind the reverse proxy, rate limiting at the proxy, audit logging of all API calls to NetApp, and a quarterly review of the IP allowlist with IT. 
Capacity shortfall. Addressed through a graduated escalation path rather than premature procurement. Tier 1 (short-term burst): non-Schrödinger workloads (Chemprop and generative-model training, OpenMM and GROMACS MD) bursted to specialist cloud GPU providers for discrete peaks, accepting that Schrödinger workloads remain on-prem due to licence binding. Tier 2 (medium-term): request reallocation of INSIIUKGPU02 (currently in the broader pool) to Computational Chemistry, contingent on sustained demand demonstrated via SLURM accounting. Tier 3 (procurement): trigger additional GPU node purchase when dev-gpu average queue wait exceeds 24 hours over a rolling 30-day window. 
