KNIME Business Hub: options to evaluate 
1. On-prem hub on existing compute. Hub services run as always-on jobs on INSIIUKCGPU01 (or INSIIUKGPU01 if H200 utilisation has slack). Lowest workflow-to-compute latency. Consumes approximately 32 to 64 GB RAM and a partial L4 share. Re-uses procured hardware; no new infrastructure ask. 
2. On-prem hub on separate infrastructure. Dedicated VM, potentially on INSIIUKCPU01 or a new small server. Clean separation; adds an infrastructure dependency. 
3. Retain GCP deployment. Zero relocation effort. Every workflow dispatching to on-prem SLURM crosses the WAN; result sets travel back to GCP for downstream steps. Recurring egress and latency cost. 
4. Hybrid: hub on GCP, executor on-prem. Uses KNIME’s distributed-executor model. The hub continues to manage workflows; executors run jobs against SLURM on-prem. Workflow latency to compute is local and the existing hub investment is preserved. Most configuration complexity; depends on Insmed’s KNIME licence terms permitting distributed executors. 
Recommendation: option 4 (hybrid) where the licence permits, otherwise option 1. Option 3 is the least suitable in the long term given the volume of workflow dispatches expected from the cluster. 
LLM serving for med chemists: options to evaluate 
1. Self-hosted open-source on the Development node. Llama 3.3 70B, Qwen 2.5 72B, or equivalent, served from INSIIUKGPU01. Best information-security position, since no project content leaves the corporate boundary. Consumes H200 capacity that would otherwise serve FEP+, MD, and training. Model quality is below leading commercial models on chemistry reasoning and multi-step tasks. Inference concurrency is limited. 
2. Commercial API with local RAG. Claude, GPT, or Gemini via an enterprise contract, with a local vector store over Insmed documents and prior project artefacts. Best model quality and lowest latency. Project content reaches the vendor inside prompts, governed by the vendor’s enterprise data-handling terms. Compliance question against Insmed’s information classification policy. 
3. Hybrid routing. Local OSS handles prompts containing sensitive markers (project codes, structures, target identities); a commercial API handles general queries (literature, methodology, code). Requires a routing classifier and a content-tagging convention. Most operationally complex; covers the IP-sensitivity case without giving up commercial-model quality entirely. 
Recommendation: the choice depends on Insmed’s policy on third-party AI vendors handling project content. Where this is acceptable under enterprise terms, option 2 is preferred. Model quality matters for chemistry queries, and self-hosting on a shared H200 reduces capacity for research workloads. Where third-party processing is not acceptable, option 3 is preferred over option 1; option 1 on its own will not meet user expectations on quality. 
